<DOC><DOCNO> AP890217-0042 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-89 0447EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief 1stLd-Writethru a0456 02-17 0419</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,380</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead of 2nd item to RESTORE word billion; picks up 2ndgraf of 2nd item, John R.</HEAD><HEAD>Foreign Visitors to U.S. Up 14 Percent in 1988</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Increasing numbers of visitors from Europe andJapan helped boost foreign tourism in the United States by 14percent last year.   The U.S. Travel and Tourism Administration also said Thursdaythat tourism is expected to continue to grow in the next two years,although not at such a quick pace.   The agency estimates that visits to the United States forbusiness and pleasure reached a record 33.7 million in 1988 andprojected there will be 35.8 million foreign visitors this year and37.2 million in 1990.   Visits by Europeans increased 24 percent last year to 5.8million, with the increase paced by a 34 percent jump in visits fromBritain. Visits from Japan also were up 24 percent, to 2.6 million.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>World Moslem Population Could Double to 1.9 Billion by 2020</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Population experts say Islam is the world'sfastest growing religion and predict the world's Moslem populationcould double to 1.9 billion people by the year 2020.   John R. Weeks, who directs the International Population Center atSan Diego State University in California, and Saad Gadalla, itstechnical director, said Thursday that about 42 babies are born toevery 1,000 people in Moslem countries each year.   That compares with fewer than 34 in other Third World countriesand only 13 in the western industrial world.   The writers said in a study, ``The Demography of IslamicNations,'' that the growth would boost the Moslem world's share ofhumanity from the current 18 percent to 25 percent by the year 2020.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>Wright Calls Off Vote on Foreign Ownership Bill</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   House Speaker Jim Wright postponed until afterPresident Bush's trip to Asia a floor vote on legislation that wouldrequire disclosure of foreign property ownership in this country.   The House had been set to vote next Thursday on the bill, whichwould require foreign owners of American property to provideinformation about their holdings to the government.   But Wright's office said Thursday that the White House indicatedit hoped there would be no vote on the bill until after Bush returnsfrom next week's trip to Japan, China and Korea.   The Reagan administration and various business critics said lastyear that the measure would stifle vitally needed foreign investmentand hurt business in other ways.</TEXT></DOC>